-- Chapters for The Agency Within
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-01', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Waiting Game', 'Riley Thompson arrived at the office at 8:27 AM, three minutes before the official start time, as always. The healthcare company''s headquarters in Boston was already buzzing with activity, but Riley''s desk in the project coordination area remained quiet.  The morning routine was unchanged for the two years Riley had worked here. Log in. Check email. Wait for direction.  The inbox held the usual overnight messages. A status update from the IT team. A meeting invitation for Thursday. A newsletter from professional development that Riley would probably never read. Nothing that required immediate action. Nothing that Riley could actually do.  So Riley waited.  The waiting wasn''t passive, exactly. Riley was good at the job. Project coordination required organization, attention to detail, the ability to track multiple workstreams and ensure nothing fell through the cracks. When tasks were assigned, Riley completed them efficiently and accurately.  But tasks were always assigned. By managers. By senior colleagues. By anyone who happened to need something done.  "Riley, can you update the project timeline?"  "Riley, can you schedule the stakeholder meeting?"  "Riley, can you pull the data for the quarterly report?"  "Of course." The response was automatic. Riley never said no. Never asked questions. Never offered alternatives. Just accepted the assignment and completed it well.  The 10 AM team meeting was typical. The department head, a woman named Patricia, stood at the front of the conference room, outlining priorities for the quarter.  "We need someone to take ownership of the patient portal redesign project," Patricia said. "It''s a significant initiative. Good visibility. Who''s interested?"  Riley''s hand stayed flat on the table. The patient portal project was interesting. Important. The kind of work that could lead to advancement. But Riley didn''t volunteer. Never volunteered. That would require putting yourself forward, making a case, taking a risk.  Instead, Riley watched as Derek, a colleague who had started six months after Riley, raised his hand.  "I''d like to take that on," Derek said. "I have some ideas about how to approach it."  Patricia nodded approvingly. "Great. Let''s talk after the meeting about next steps."  Riley felt a familiar pang. Not jealousy, exactly. More like a quiet ache. The project could have been Riley''s. But asking for it felt impossible. What if Derek was better suited? What if Patricia didn''t think Riley was ready? What if volunteering made Riley look pushy?  Better to wait. To be assigned. To be safe.  The afternoon was spent on assigned tasks. Updating a project schedule. Coordinating a meeting between departments. Preparing a status report. Work that Riley could do well, work that kept the projects moving, work that no one noticed because it was expected.  "Good work on the timeline," Patricia said in passing. "Keep it up."  The praise was nice. But it was generic. The kind of acknowledgment given to someone who met expectations, not someone who exceeded them. Riley had been meeting expectations for two years.  The evening commute was spent, as always, scrolling through phone notifications. LinkedIn updates about colleagues getting promoted. Instagram posts about people''s exciting projects. The evidence of other people''s growth, other people''s initiative, other people''s lives moving forward.  Riley''s apartment was small and quiet. Dinner was takeout eaten while watching television. The day had been fine. Productive, even. But something was missing. Something had been missing for a long time.  The question surfaced, as it sometimes did in the quiet of the evening. What would it feel like to want something and ask for it? To see an opportunity and take it? To stop waiting for permission and just... act?  The question had no answer. Riley had never tried. The waiting was too ingrained, too comfortable, too safe.  But as sleep approached, another thought emerged. What was the cost of all this waiting? What opportunities had been missed? What growth had been forfeited?  The questions lingered at the edge of consciousness, uncomfortable but persistent. Something was wrong. Riley couldn''t name it yet. But it was there, a quiet dissatisfaction that had been building for months.  Tomorrow would be another day of waiting. Another day of being assigned. Another day of meeting expectations and nothing more.  But somewhere beneath the comfort of the routine, the first crack was forming. The first hint that the waiting game might have costs that weren''t immediately visible.  The morning would come, and with it, the familiar pattern. But something had shifted, even if Riley couldn''t yet admit it. The waiting was safe. But safe wasn''t the same as enough.', NULL, 1, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-02', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Missed Moment', 'The opportunity came on a Wednesday morning, in an email that made Riley''s breath catch.  The company was launching a new initiative. A cross-functional project to improve patient experience across all touchpoints. Strategy, technology, design, operations. Everything Riley found interesting, everything that seemed important, everything that could transform a career.  Patricia stood at the front of the conference room, describing the scope.  "This is a flagship project for the year. Executive visibility. Significant budget. We need someone to coordinate the workstreams and ensure integration across teams."  Riley''s heart rate quickened. This was it. The kind of opportunity that came once in a career. The kind of project that could change everything.  "I''m looking for someone to step up and take ownership," Patricia continued. "This isn''t an assignment. I need someone to volunteer. To say they want it."  The room was quiet. Riley''s hand stayed flat on the table, as always. But something was different this time. A voice inside was screaming. Say something. Raise your hand. This is what you''ve been waiting for.  But the familiar fears crowded in. What if you''re not ready? What if someone else is better? What if you volunteer and regret it? What if Patricia doesn''t think you''re capable?  The internal debate raged while the external silence stretched.  "I''ll do it."  The voice came from across the table. Derek, again. Confident, as always.  "I''ve been thinking about patient experience for a while," Derek continued. "I have some initial ideas about how to structure the workstreams. I''d love to discuss them with you, Patricia."  Patricia''s face lit up. "Excellent. That''s exactly the kind of initiative I was hoping for. Let''s schedule time tomorrow to talk through your approach."  The meeting continued, but Riley stopped listening. The opportunity had been there. Riley had wanted it. And Riley had let it pass.  The rest of the day was a blur of assigned tasks. Riley completed them efficiently, as always. But the satisfaction was gone. Each completed item felt like evidence of what could have been.  Derek walked by Riley''s desk in the afternoon, energy visible in every step.  "Hey, do you have the latest patient satisfaction data?" Derek asked. "I want to include it in my project proposal."  "Of course." Riley pulled up the file. "Here you go."  "Thanks. This project is going to be amazing. I can already see how to approach it."  Riley watched Derek walk away, the data that Riley had compiled being used for the project that Riley should have led.  That evening, the apartment felt smaller than usual. The takeout container sat half-empty on the coffee table. The television played something Riley wasn''t watching.  The question that had been hovering finally landed. Why didn''t you say anything?  The answer came in fragments. Fear. Habit. The deep belief that opportunities were given, not taken. The assumption that waiting was the professional thing to do.  But watching Derek take the project, seeing the energy and purpose that came from choosing rather than being chosen, Riley felt the cost of all that waiting.  Derek wasn''t smarter. Wasn''t more experienced. Wasn''t more capable. Derek had simply raised a hand. Said words. Taken action.  The difference between Riley''s day and Derek''s day was one moment of initiative. One choice to speak instead of stay silent.  Riley lay in bed, staring at the ceiling. The regret was a physical weight, pressing down on the chest. Not dramatic, not overwhelming, but persistent. The quiet ache of a life that could be different.  What would it feel like to want something and ask for it? The question from the night before returned. But now it had a companion question. What does it feel like to want something and not ask?  The answer was clear now. It felt like this. Like watching opportunities pass. Like being invisible while others became visible. Like meeting expectations while others exceeded them.  The morning would come, and with it, the familiar routine. But something had shifted. The cost of waiting was no longer theoretical. It was real, and it hurt.  Riley didn''t know what to do with the hurt. Didn''t know how to change the pattern. But for the first time, the desire to change was stronger than the comfort of staying the same.  The missed moment was gone. But maybe, just maybe, it had revealed something important. The waiting game had a price. And Riley was finally starting to pay attention to it.', NULL, 2, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-03', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Spark', 'The regret from the missed opportunity lingered for days. Riley completed assigned tasks, attended meetings, maintained the routine. But something had shifted. The comfort of waiting had been replaced by a restless dissatisfaction.  Thursday afternoon, Riley found herself standing outside Angela Washington''s office. Angela was a senior director, someone Riley had admired from a distance. Her presence in meetings was commanding but not intimidating. She spoke with purpose, acted with confidence, seemed to move through the world with an ease that Riley had never known.  The door was open. Angela looked up from her computer.  "Riley, right? Can I help you?"  The words came before Riley could second-guess them. "I was wondering if you had a few minutes. I wanted to ask you something."  Angela''s expression shifted to curiosity. "Of course. Come in."  The office was warm and organized. Angela gestured to a chair across from her desk.  "What''s on your mind?"  Riley sat, suddenly aware of how unusual this was. Approaching a senior director without an agenda. Asking for time without a specific request. This wasn''t how Riley operated.  "I saw you in the leadership meeting yesterday," Riley began. "You proposed that new approach to the quality metrics. It was... impressive. You just spoke up, offered an idea, and everyone listened."  Angela smiled slightly. "Thank you. But I suspect there''s more on your mind than flattery."  Riley took a breath. "How do you do that? How do you just... speak up? Take initiative? I''ve been here two years, and I''ve never once volunteered for anything. I wait to be assigned. I complete tasks. I meet expectations. And I''m watching opportunities pass me by."  The admission was more honest than Riley had intended. But Angela''s expression remained open.  "That''s a good question. And it''s one I asked myself, about fifteen years ago." Angela leaned back in her chair. "I used to be like you. Waiting for direction. Afraid to overstep. Convinced that my job was to do what I was told."  "What changed?"  "I realized that waiting is a choice. A choice to let others determine your path. A choice to be reactive instead of proactive." Angela paused. "I call it agency. The power to act. To decide what needs to happen and make it happen."  "But how do you know what to do? What if you''re wrong?"  "You don''t know. You''re sometimes wrong. That''s part of it." Angela''s voice was gentle but direct. "Agency isn''t about being right all the time. It''s about taking ownership of your choices. Including the choice to try something that might not work."  Riley absorbed this. "I''ve always thought my job was to wait for direction. That taking initiative was... overstepping."  "That''s a common belief. Especially for people who are good at following instructions." Angela smiled. "But here''s the thing. The people who advance, who create impact, who build careers worth having, they''re not waiting for permission. They''re looking for opportunities to contribute. And when they don''t see opportunities, they create them."  "How do I start?"  Angela considered the question. "Start small. Look for problems that need solving. Offer solutions instead of just identifying issues. Take one action each day that you weren''t told to take."  "That sounds terrifying."  "It is, at first. But the fear diminishes with practice. And the rewards are significant." Angela leaned forward. "Riley, I''ve noticed your work. You''re capable. Organized. Detail-oriented. You could be doing much more than coordinating other people''s projects. But no one''s going to hand you that opportunity. You have to take it."  The conversation continued for another twenty minutes. Angela shared stories of her own journey, the small initiatives that had built her reputation, the failures that had taught her lessons, the gradual development of confidence that came from action.  Walking back to the desk, Riley felt something unfamiliar. Not certainty, but possibility. The beginning of a different way of seeing.  The rest of the afternoon was spent differently. Instead of waiting for the next assignment, Riley looked at the current projects with new eyes. What problems existed? What improvements could be made? What small actions could be taken without permission?  The answers were there, if Riley looked for them. The project tracking system was inefficient. The meeting scheduling process was cumbersome. The status reports could be more informative.  These weren''t dramatic opportunities. They weren''t the patient experience initiative that Derek had claimed. But they were something. Places where Riley could act instead of wait.  That evening, the apartment didn''t feel as small. The questions that had haunted Riley for weeks now had a different quality. Not just what was wrong, but what could be done.  Agency. The power to act. The choice to stop waiting.  Riley didn''t know if this would work. Didn''t know if the fear could be overcome. But for the first time, there was a direction. A possibility. A spark.  The morning would come, and with it, the chance to try something different. Not a dramatic transformation, but a small step. One action that wasn''t assigned. One choice to act instead of wait.  The waiting game wasn''t over. But maybe it didn''t have to be the only game Riley played.', NULL, 3, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-04', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Fear', 'Monday morning arrived with a resolution. Riley would take action. Not dramatic action, not world-changing action, but something. One small initiative that wasn''t assigned.  The morning routine felt different. Instead of checking email and waiting, Riley opened the project tracking system. The inefficiency that had been noticed on Thursday was still there. A process that could be improved.  Riley began drafting a proposal. Nothing elaborate. Just a suggestion for streamlining the status update workflow. A small change that could save time for everyone.  The cursor blinked on the screen. The email to Patricia was ready to send. All it required was pressing a button.  But the fears crowded in. What if this is presumptuous? What if Patricia thinks you''re overstepping? What if the idea is stupid? What if you send this and regret it?  The cursor blinked. Riley''s finger hovered over the mouse.  The email was closed without sending. Maybe tomorrow. Maybe when the idea was more developed. Maybe when Riley felt more confident.  Tuesday brought another opportunity. A meeting where Patricia asked for input on the quarterly planning process. Riley had opinions. Had ideas about how to make the planning more effective.  But when the moment came to speak, the words stayed inside. Someone else offered a suggestion. Patricia nodded approvingly. Riley stayed silent.  Wednesday, Thursday, Friday. Each day brought opportunities. Each day, Riley found reasons to wait. The fear was too strong. The habit too ingrained. The comfort of passivity too appealing.  By Friday afternoon, the resolution from Monday felt like a distant memory. The pattern had reasserted itself. Waiting. Being assigned. Playing it safe.  But something was different now. The dissatisfaction was sharper. The awareness of what was being lost was clearer.  Riley sat at the desk, staring at the project tracking system. The inefficiency was still there. The opportunity was still there. The fear was still there.  The phone rang. It was Dr. James Park, an executive coach that the company made available to employees who wanted development support. Riley had scheduled a session weeks ago, before the missed opportunity, before the conversation with Angela.  "Riley, are we still on for this afternoon?"  The session happened in a small conference room. Dr. Park was older, with the kind of calm presence that came from decades of helping people navigate their careers.  "So tell me what''s been on your mind," Dr. Park began.  The story came out. The missed opportunity. The conversation with Angela. The resolution to take action. The failures of the past week. The fear that seemed insurmountable.  Dr. Park listened without interruption. When Riley finished, he nodded slowly.  "What''s the worst that could happen if you took initiative?"  The question was simple, but Riley had never actually articulated the answer.  "I could be wrong. I could look stupid. I could overstep and get in trouble."  "Let''s examine each of those. If you were wrong about a small suggestion, what would actually happen?"  Riley considered. "Patricia would probably just say no. Or suggest an alternative."  "And if you looked stupid? What would happen?"  "People might think less of me. But... they probably wouldn''t think about me at all. They''d just move on."  "And if you overstepped?"  "Patricia might tell me to stay in my lane. But she''s never actually done that to anyone. She encourages people to contribute."  Dr. Park leaned forward. "Now, what''s the worst that''s happening by not taking initiative?"  The question landed with force. Riley had never considered it this way.  "I''m invisible. I''m watching opportunities pass. I''m staying in the same place while others advance. I''m..." Riley paused. "I''m disappearing. I''m becoming invisible. I''m watching my life pass by while I wait for permission."  "That sounds worse than any of the fears you named."  The truth of it was undeniable. The cost of inaction was higher than the cost of action. But the fear didn''t disappear just because the logic was clear.  "How do I overcome the fear?"  "You don''t overcome it. You act despite it." Dr. Park''s voice was gentle. "Fear is a natural response to doing something new. The question isn''t how to eliminate fear. The question is whether you''ll let fear make your decisions for you."  The session continued, exploring the roots of the fear, the patterns that had developed over years, the small steps that could build confidence. By the end, Riley had a different perspective.  Not the absence of fear. But a path forward despite the fear.  Walking home that evening, Riley felt the weight of the week. The failed resolution. The missed opportunities. The fear that had won, again.  But something else was there too. The recognition that the fear was a choice. Not a conscious choice, but a choice nonetheless. And choices could be changed.  The apartment was quiet. The takeout was ordered. The television was on.  But Riley didn''t sit down. Instead, the laptop was opened. The proposal for the project tracking system was pulled up.  The cursor blinked. The fear was there, whispering its warnings.  But the cost of waiting was clearer now. The price of passivity was higher than the price of action.  Riley''s finger hovered over the mouse. The fear screamed.  But this time, Riley pressed send.  The email was gone. The action was taken. The fear was still there, but it was no longer in control.  The response came the next morning. Patricia had replied.  "Great idea, Riley. Let''s discuss this at our next one-on-one. I''d like to hear more about your thoughts on process improvement."  Riley stared at the email, feeling something unfamiliar. Not the absence of fear. But the presence of something else. Agency. The power to act. The choice to stop waiting.  The fear was still there. But it was no longer the only voice.', NULL, 4, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-05', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The First Step', 'The one-on-one with Patricia was scheduled for Wednesday. Three days to prepare, to worry, to second-guess the email that had already been sent.  But Riley didn''t spend the time spiraling. Instead, the preparation was deliberate. The proposal was refined. Implementation steps were outlined. Potential objections were anticipated.  This was different from the usual approach to meetings. Usually, Riley showed up and waited for direction. This time, Riley was bringing something. Offering something. Taking initiative.  The fear was still there. But it was quieter now. The act of sending the email had broken something. The worst hadn''t happened. Patricia had responded positively. The fear''s predictions had been wrong.  Wednesday morning, Riley walked into Patricia''s office with a printed proposal and a racing heart.  "Thanks for making time," Riley said, the words coming more confidently than expected.  "Of course. I was glad to see you taking initiative. That''s exactly the kind of engagement I''m looking for from the team."  The conversation that followed was different from any Riley had experienced in two years at the company. Instead of receiving assignments, Riley was presenting ideas. Instead of waiting for direction, Riley was offering direction.  "The current tracking system requires three separate updates for each project," Riley explained. "I propose consolidating into a single dashboard that updates automatically. It would save about two hours per week for each project coordinator."  Patricia nodded, looking at the proposal. "What would you need to implement this?"  The question was unexpected. Riley had prepared to defend the idea, not to discuss implementation.  "I''d need access to the dashboard tools. Maybe some training on the automation features. And coordination with IT to ensure the data flows correctly."  "Can you put together a plan? Timeline, resources needed, expected outcomes?"  Riley felt a surge of something unfamiliar. Not just relief, but excitement. Patricia wasn''t just accepting the idea. She was giving Riley ownership of it.  "I can have that to you by Friday."  "Perfect. This is good work, Riley. I''d like to see more of this kind of thinking."  Walking back to the desk, Riley felt transformed. Not dramatically, not completely, but noticeably. The first step had been taken. The waiting pattern had been broken.  The rest of the week was spent developing the implementation plan. Riley worked on it between assigned tasks, staying late to refine the details, arriving early to research best practices.  The fear was still there, especially when the plan was sent to Patricia on Friday afternoon. But it was manageable now. A background noise instead of a wall.  The response came within an hour.  "This is excellent. You have approval to proceed. Let me know what support you need."  Riley stared at the email, feeling the weight of what had just happened. Not just approval, but ownership. Riley was now responsible for something that hadn''t existed before. Something that had emerged from Riley''s initiative, not from someone else''s assignment.  The implementation took three weeks. There were challenges, setbacks, moments when the fear resurged. But Riley worked through them, asking for help when needed, adjusting the approach when necessary, persisting when things got difficult.  The dashboard launched on a Thursday morning. By Friday afternoon, the feedback was coming in.  "This is so much better," a colleague said. "I can''t believe we were doing it the old way."  "Who set this up?" another asked. "It''s really well designed."  "Riley did," Patricia said, walking by. "Great work."  The recognition was nice. But the real reward was internal. The feeling of having created something. Of having acted instead of waited. Of having taken a step, however small, toward a different kind of career.  That evening, Riley sat in the apartment, reflecting on the past month. The missed opportunity that had started the journey. The conversation with Angela that had provided direction. The fear that had almost won. The first step that had broken the pattern.  The waiting game wasn''t over. The fear wasn''t gone. But something had changed. Riley had discovered something that had always been there, hidden beneath the passivity.  Agency. The power to act. The choice to stop waiting.  The first step had been taken. And it had led somewhere worth going.', NULL, 5, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-06', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Resistance', 'The success of the dashboard project emboldened Riley. What had seemed impossible a month ago now felt achievable. The fear was still there, but it was manageable. The pattern of waiting was still ingrained, but it was no longer unbreakable.  The following weeks brought more initiatives. A proposal for improving the meeting scheduling process. A suggestion for streamlining the quarterly reporting. Small improvements that added up to visible contributions.  But the changes didn''t go unnoticed by everyone.  "You''ve been really... assertive lately."  The comment came from a colleague named Marcus, someone Riley had worked alongside for the entire two years at the company. His tone was neutral, but something in his expression suggested discomfort.  "I''ve been trying to contribute more," Riley said carefully. "Take more initiative."  "It''s just... different. You used to be more..." Marcus trailed off.  "More what?"  "I don''t know. More... collaborative? More willing to let others lead?"  The words stung, even though Riley couldn''t quite articulate why. Being collaborative and letting others lead had been the problem, not the solution. But Marcus''s discomfort was real.  The resistance continued in subtle ways. Meetings where Riley''s suggestions were met with silence. Conversations where colleagues seemed to pull back. A sense that the familiar patterns were being disrupted and not everyone appreciated the disruption.  By the end of the second week, the fear had returned in full force. Not the fear of taking action, but a new fear. The fear of being seen as pushy. Overstepping. Changing in ways that made others uncomfortable.  Riley sat at the desk, staring at the latest proposal. A suggestion for improving the project handoff process. It was a good idea. It would save time and reduce errors. But after Marcus''s comment and the subtle resistance from others, the cursor blinked without being sent.  The doubt was corrosive. Maybe this was a mistake. Maybe the old way was better. Maybe Riley should go back to waiting, to being assigned, to the comfortable invisibility that had defined the first two years.  The meeting with Angela was scheduled for that afternoon. Riley walked in with the doubt visible in every step.  "You look like you''re carrying something heavy," Angela observed.  The story came out. The initial success. The growing confidence. The resistance from colleagues. The doubt that had returned.  Angela listened without interruption. When Riley finished, she nodded slowly.  "Resistance doesn''t mean you''re wrong. It means you''re changing things. That''s uncomfortable for people."  "But Marcus said I used to be more collaborative. What if I''m being too aggressive?"  "Let me ask you something. When Derek took the patient experience project, when others volunteer for opportunities, do people call them aggressive?"  Riley considered. "No. They''re seen as... ambitious. Proactive. Leaders."  "Exactly. There''s a double standard that people who start taking initiative often face. Especially if they''ve been passive before. The people around them are used to a certain pattern. When that pattern changes, it''s uncomfortable."  "So what do I do?"  Angela leaned forward. "You keep going. You acknowledge the discomfort others feel, but you don''t let their discomfort become your limitation. You''re not responsible for their comfort. You''re responsible for your growth."  The words were challenging, but they felt true. Riley had spent two years prioritizing others'' comfort over personal growth. The result had been invisibility, stagnation, the quiet ache of a life not fully lived.  "But how do I handle the pushback?"  "You stay professional. You listen to feedback. But you also recognize that not all feedback is valid. Some of it is just people adjusting to change." Angela paused. "And you find allies. People who support your growth. People who appreciate what you''re contributing."  The conversation continued, exploring strategies for handling resistance, for maintaining confidence in the face of doubt, for persisting when the path became difficult.  Walking back to the desk, Riley felt the doubt receding. Not disappearing, but becoming manageable. The resistance was real, but it wasn''t a sign of failure. It was a sign of change.  The proposal for the project handoff process was still on the screen. The cursor still blinked. The fear was still there.  But something else was there too. The recognition that the old way wasn''t working. That the comfort of passivity had a cost. That the resistance from others was their problem to manage, not Riley''s problem to solve.  The proposal was sent. The resistance continued. But Riley persisted.  And slowly, over the following weeks, something shifted. The colleagues who had been uncomfortable began to adjust. The suggestions that had been met with silence started generating discussion. The resistance didn''t disappear, but it diminished.  Riley learned something important in those weeks. Agency wasn''t just about taking action. It was about persisting through the discomfort that action created. Not just in oneself, but in others.  The waiting game was truly over. And the game that replaced it was harder, but also more rewarding.  The resistance had been faced. And Riley was still standing.', NULL, 6, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-07', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Practice', 'The resistance had been faced, but the journey wasn''t over. Riley understood now that agency wasn''t a single decision, but a practice. Something that needed to be cultivated, maintained, strengthened.  The Sunday evening journal session became a ritual. Riley sat at the small desk in the apartment, reviewing the past week and planning the next one. Not just tasks to complete, but initiatives to take. Opportunities to seize. Actions that weren''t assigned.  The first week of the practice was difficult. Old habits resurfaced. Moments of hesitation stretched into missed opportunities. The fear, though quieter, still influenced decisions.  But Riley persisted. Each day, at least one action that wasn''t assigned. One suggestion that wasn''t requested. One initiative that wasn''t required.  The dashboard project had been the breakthrough, but the practice was what sustained it. Small actions, accumulated over time, building a new pattern.  By the second week, the rhythm was emerging. Morning review of potential opportunities. Mid-day action on at least one initiative. Evening reflection on what had worked and what hadn''t.  The practice wasn''t dramatic. It wasn''t the patient experience project that Derek had claimed. It was smaller, more incremental. But it was consistent.  The third week brought a new challenge. Patricia announced a reorganization of the project coordination function. New responsibilities. New opportunities. New uncertainty.  In the past, Riley would have waited to see how the reorganization affected assignments. Would have hoped for the best while preparing for the worst. Would have been passive while others positioned themselves.  But the practice had changed something.  Riley requested a meeting with Patricia. Not to ask for direction, but to offer input.  "I''ve been thinking about the reorganization," Riley said. "I have some ideas about how the new structure could work. May I share them?"  Patricia''s expression showed surprise, but also interest. "Of course."  The ideas had been developed over the weekend, refined in the journal sessions, practiced in Riley''s mind. They weren''t perfect. They weren''t comprehensive. But they were something. A contribution rather than a request.  "That''s thoughtful input," Patricia said when Riley finished. "I''ll incorporate some of these ideas into the plan. And I''d like you to be involved in the implementation."  The meeting ended with Riley owning a piece of the reorganization. Not because it had been assigned, but because it had been claimed.  The following weeks were busy. The reorganization required coordination, communication, problem-solving. Riley was in the middle of it, not as a passive recipient of change, but as an active shaper of it.  The practice continued. Daily initiatives. Weekly reflections. The steady accumulation of agency.  By the end of the month, something had shifted. The fear was still there, especially when new challenges arose. But it was manageable now. A familiar companion rather than an insurmountable obstacle.  The meeting with Angela happened on a Friday afternoon.  "Something''s different about you," Angela observed. "You''re more... present. More engaged. What changed?"  Riley considered the question. "I''ve been practicing. Taking initiative every day, even when it''s hard. It''s becoming... easier."  "That''s how it works. Agency is a muscle. You''re building it. It gets stronger with practice."  The conversation continued, reflecting on the journey, the challenges, the growth. By the time it ended, Riley felt the quiet satisfaction of progress.  Walking home that evening, the city felt different. Not because it had changed, but because Riley had changed. The passive observer had become an active participant. The waiter had become a doer.  The practice wasn''t dramatic. It wasn''t a single transformation that changed everything overnight. It was incremental, cumulative, sometimes frustratingly slow.  But it was real. And it was sustainable.  The morning would come, and with it, the next opportunity to practice. The next chance to act instead of wait. The next step in the journey from passivity to agency.  The waiting game was over. The practice had begun. And the practice was changing everything.', NULL, 7, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-08', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Impact', 'The reorganization was complete, and Riley''s role had expanded. Not just project coordination anymore, but process improvement. A formal responsibility that had emerged from informal initiatives.  The impact was visible in ways that Riley hadn''t anticipated. The dashboard that had been the first initiative was now used across three departments. The meeting scheduling improvements had saved an estimated forty hours per month. The project handoff process that had faced resistance was now standard practice.  But the real impact was harder to measure. It was in the way colleagues approached Riley for input. In the invitations to planning meetings that hadn''t existed before. In the sense that Riley had become someone who contributed, not just completed.  The quarterly review with Patricia was scheduled for a Thursday afternoon.  "I want to talk about your trajectory," Patricia said, settling into her chair. "The past three months have been remarkable. You''ve transformed your approach to work."  Riley felt a flush of pride, but also uncertainty. "It hasn''t been easy. The fear is still there sometimes."  "That''s normal. The fear doesn''t disappear. But you''ve learned to work with it." Patricia leaned forward. "I''d like to offer you a new opportunity. There''s a strategic initiative starting next quarter. Cross-functional. High visibility. I think you''re ready to lead it."  The words landed with weight. Lead. Not coordinate. Not support. Lead.  "I''d like that," Riley said, the words coming more confidently than expected. "Can you tell me more about the scope?"  The conversation continued, outlining the initiative, the expectations, the support that would be available. By the end, Riley owned something that would have seemed impossible three months ago.  Walking back to the desk, Riley passed the conference room where the patient experience project was being discussed. Derek was presenting, confident and commanding. The project that Riley had let pass.  But the regret that had once been sharp was now dull. Derek''s project was Derek''s. Riley had found a different path. Not through being assigned, but through claiming. Not through waiting, but through acting.  The afternoon was spent reviewing the new initiative. The scope was significant. The stakes were high. The fear was there, whispering its warnings.  But something else was there too. The confidence that came from practice. The knowledge that action was possible, even when fear was present. The recognition that the cost of waiting was higher than the cost of trying.  The meeting with Angela happened the following week. Riley shared the news about the new initiative, the expanded role, the visible impact of the past months.  "You''ve discovered something most people never find," Angela said. "The power to act. The question now is how you''ll use it."  "What do you mean?"  "Agency isn''t just about personal advancement. It''s about impact. The more you develop your ability to act, the more responsibility you have to use it well."  The words were challenging, but they felt important. Riley had been focused on personal transformation. But Angela was pointing toward something larger. The responsibility that came with capability.  "How do I do that?"  "You keep growing. You help others find their agency. You use your power to create value, not just for yourself, but for everyone around you."  The conversation continued, exploring the implications of agency, the responsibilities that came with growth, the opportunities to multiply impact by helping others.  Walking home that evening, Riley felt the weight of the journey. Not just the personal transformation, but the recognition of what it meant. The power to act was also a responsibility to act. The ability to choose was also an obligation to choose well.  The impact was visible now. In the metrics that had improved. In the processes that had been streamlined. In the role that had expanded.  But the real impact was internal. The transformation from passive to active. From waiting to acting. From invisible to visible.  The morning would come, and with it, the new initiative. The chance to lead. The opportunity to create impact beyond personal advancement.  The waiting game was over. The practice was established. And now, the impact was becoming real.', NULL, 8, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-09', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Leadership', 'The strategic initiative was called Project Phoenix. A comprehensive redesign of the patient intake process across all facilities. Technology, training, communication, measurement. Everything Riley found interesting, everything that seemed important.  And Riley was leading it.  The first team meeting was scheduled for a Monday morning. Five people from different departments, all more experienced than Riley in their respective areas. All looking to Riley for direction.  The old fear surfaced immediately. Who were you to lead these people? What made you think you could do this? Shouldn''t you wait for someone more qualified?  But the practice had built something. Not the absence of fear, but the ability to act despite it.  "Thank you all for being here," Riley began. "This project is important, and I''m glad to be working with you. I want to start by hearing your perspectives on the current intake process. What''s working? What isn''t? What should we focus on first?"  The meeting unfolded differently from what Riley had expected. Instead of directing, Riley was facilitating. Instead of having all the answers, Riley was asking questions. Instead of controlling, Riley was enabling.  The team responded. Ideas emerged. Solutions developed. By the end of the meeting, the project had direction that had come from the collective, not from Riley alone.  The following weeks were a learning experience. Riley discovered that leadership wasn''t about doing everything. It was about creating conditions for others to do their best work.  But the old patterns still surfaced. Moments when Riley wanted to take over, to control, to ensure everything was done right. The fear of failure manifesting as micromanagement.  The conversation with Angela happened after a particularly difficult team meeting.  "I''m struggling," Riley admitted. "I thought leadership meant having the answers. But I don''t have all the answers. And when I try to control everything, the team pulls back."  Angela nodded. "You''re discovering something important. Leadership isn''t about having all the answers. It''s about creating space for others to find answers. It''s about distributing agency, not concentrating it."  "How do I do that?"  "You ask questions instead of giving directions. You create frameworks instead of specific solutions. You trust people to do their jobs while providing support when they need it."  The conversation continued, exploring the connection between personal agency and leadership. The recognition that leading was about helping others find their power to act.  The following weeks brought experimentation. Riley tried different approaches. Some worked. Some didn''t. The practice of leadership developed alongside the practice of agency.  The breakthrough came in the fourth week. A team member named Priya approached with a problem.  "I''m stuck on the technology implementation. I''m not sure how to proceed."  In the past, Riley would have offered a solution. Would have taken ownership of the problem. Would have done the work that Priya should do.  But the new understanding was there.  "What have you considered so far?" Riley asked.  Priya outlined several approaches. Each had merits. Each had challenges.  "What do you think is the best path forward?"  Priya considered. "I think the second option has the most potential. But I''m worried about the timeline."  "What would you need to make that timeline work?"  The conversation continued, with Riley asking questions and Priya developing solutions. By the end, Priya owned a path forward that she had created, not one that had been assigned.  "Thanks for talking this through," Priya said. "I know what to do now."  Riley felt a different kind of satisfaction. Not the pride of having solved a problem, but the quieter satisfaction of having helped someone else solve it.  The project progressed. The team grew more capable. Riley grew more comfortable with a leadership style that emphasized enablement over control.  The celebration happened at the end of the quarter. Project Phoenix had launched successfully. The metrics were positive. The team was energized.  "Great leadership," Patricia said, clapping Riley on the shoulder. "You should be proud of what you''ve accomplished."  But Riley felt proud of something different. Not the accomplishment, but the team. Not the control, but the distribution of agency. Not the leadership, but the enablement.  The meeting with Angela happened the following week.  "You''ve discovered something important," Angela said. "Leadership isn''t about doing. It''s about enabling. You learned to act for yourself. Now you''re learning to help others act for themselves."  "It''s harder than I expected. Letting go of control."  "It is. But it''s also more powerful. One person''s agency is limited. A team''s agency is multiplied."  Riley considered the journey. From waiting to acting. From acting to leading. From leading to enabling. Each step had built on the previous one. Each transformation had prepared the next.  The morning would come, and with it, new challenges. New opportunities to practice. New chances to help others find their agency.  The waiting game was over. The practice was established. The impact was visible. And now, the leadership was emerging.  Not control, but enablement. Not direction, but distribution. Not power over, but power through.  The agency that had been discovered was now being multiplied. And that multiplication was the real leadership.', NULL, 9, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
INSERT INTO chapters (chapter_id, book_id, title, content, selected_cards, order_num, created_at)
VALUES ('chapter-coo-the-agency-within-10', 'preset-coo-the-agency-within', 'The Agency Advantage', 'Six months had passed since the conversation with Angela that had started everything. Six months of practice, of struggle, of transformation.  Riley stood at the window of the office, looking out at the Boston skyline, and tried to remember who that person had been. The one who waited for direction. Who never volunteered. Who met expectations and nothing more.  That person felt like a stranger now.  The morning routine was different. Not the passive checking of email, waiting for assignments. But an active review of opportunities. What could be improved? What could be created? What action could be taken today that wasn''t assigned?  The practice had become automatic. Not effortless, but natural. The fear was still there, especially when new challenges arose. But it was a familiar companion now, not a wall.  Project Phoenix had been followed by other initiatives. Each had built on the previous one. Each had developed new capabilities. Each had expanded Riley''s impact.  The team had grown too. Not just in size, but in capability. The agency that Riley had developed was now distributed. Each team member had found their own power to act.  The morning meeting was typical now. Riley gathered the team, not to assign tasks, but to coordinate initiatives. Each person reported on what they were driving. Each person owned something. Each person acted.  "The intake process improvements are showing results," Priya reported. "Patient satisfaction is up twelve percent. I''m working on the next phase now."  "Great work," Riley said. "What support do you need?"  The question was different from the old approach. Not "here''s what you should do," but "what do you need to do what you''ve decided?"  The meeting continued, each team member reporting, each owning their piece, each exercising the agency that Riley had learned to enable.  The afternoon brought a meeting with Angela. They had stayed in regular contact, the mentor relationship evolving into something more like partnership.  "You''ve built something remarkable," Angela said, looking at the reports Riley had brought. "Not just personal agency, but distributed agency. A team that acts instead of waits."  "It wasn''t easy. And it''s not finished. The fear still surfaces sometimes."  "That''s normal. The fear never completely disappears. But you''ve learned to work with it instead of against it." Angela paused. "What''s next for you?"  Riley considered the question. The role had expanded. The team had grown. The impact was visible. But something was still emerging.  "I want to help others find what I found. Not just my team, but anyone who''s stuck in the waiting game. Anyone who''s invisible because they''re waiting to be seen."  "That''s the natural progression. You discovered agency. You built it into practice. You learned to distribute it through leadership. The next step is teaching it."  The conversation continued, exploring what teaching might look like. Workshops. Mentorship. A framework that could help others find their power to act.  Walking home that evening, Riley felt the direction crystallizing. The journey from waiting to acting had been personal. But the journey from acting to teaching was about others.  The apartment was quiet. The evening routine was different now. Not the passive consumption of television, but active reflection. Journaling. Planning. Preparing for the next day''s practice.  The phone buzzed with a message from Dr. Park, the executive coach who had helped in the early days.  Heard about your promotion. Congratulations. You''ve come a long way from the person who sat in my office afraid to send an email.  Riley smiled at the memory. The fear that had seemed insurmountable. The email that had felt like a mountain. The first step that had changed everything.  The response was typed quickly. Thank you for helping me see that the fear was a choice. That''s the lesson I want to share with others.  The night was quiet, but the silence felt different. Not the isolation of the waiting game, but the peace of purposeful work.  Riley sat at the desk, opening the journal. The practice continued. Not because it was required, but because it was valuable. Not because someone assigned it, but because it had become part of who Riley was.  The agency advantage wasn''t just about career advancement. It was about living differently. About choosing instead of waiting. About acting instead of reacting. About creating instead of just completing.  The morning would come, and with it, new opportunities. New chances to practice. New people to help. New ways to multiply the agency that had been discovered.  The waiting game was over. The practice was established. The impact was visible. The leadership was emerging. And the teaching was calling.  Riley closed the journal, feeling the quiet satisfaction of a journey that had just begun. The agency that had seemed so foreign, so impossible, was now a foundation. Not the end of the story, but the beginning.  The power to act. The choice to stop waiting. The agency within.  It had been there all along. It just needed to be discovered. And now, it needed to be shared.  The morning would come. And Riley would be ready.', NULL, 10, '2026-03-29 23:55:52');
